#---DATA-----------------------------------------------------------------
data <- read.csv("DrugData.txt", sep = " ")
head(data)
##   time    price generic
## 1    1 76.03781       0
## 2    2 76.16505       0
## 3    3 76.10777       0
## 4    4 76.29946       0
## 5    5 76.71367       0
## 6    6 76.04275       0
time <- data$time
data$one <-  I((time <= 19) * (time ))
data$two <-  I((time >= 20 & time <=30 ) * (time - 19))
data$three <- I((time >= 31) * (time - 30))
data$one <- data$one * as.numeric(!(as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))))
data$two <- data$two * as.numeric(!(as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))))
data$three <- data$three * as.numeric(!(as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))))

data$four <- I((time >= 25) * (time - 24))
data$four <- data$four * as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))


data$inter <- NA

data[data$one != 0,"inter"] <- 1
data[data$two != 0 ,"inter"] <- 2
data[data$three != 0,"inter"] <- 3
data[data$four != 0, "inter"] <- 4
data$inter <- as.factor(data$inter)
data$generic <- as.factor(data$generic)

#BUGSIntercepts
data$i1 <- I(time <= 19) * as.numeric(!(as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))))
data$i2 <- I(time >= 20 & time <=30) * as.numeric(!(as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))))
data$i3 <- I(time >= 31) * as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))
data$i4 <- I(time >= 25) * as.numeric(as.character((data$generic)))

FREQENTIST

#---Frequentist----------------------------------------------------------
#Using -1 to get rid of general intercept and using 1|inter to generate both b0 and the other (offset) intercepts
#time serves as the slope of the generic drugs, with one two and three being offsets
m <- lmer(price ~ -1 + time  + (1|inter) + one + two + three, data = data,
          REML = F)
summary(m)
## Linear mixed model fit by maximum likelihood t-tests use Satterthwaite
##   approximations to degrees of freedom [lmerMod]
## Formula: price ~ -1 + time + (1 | inter) + one + two + three

BAYESIAN

#---OpenBUGS-------------------------------------------------------------
mod <- function(){
  for (t in 1:74){
    price[t] ~ dnorm(eta[t],tauC)
    eta[t] <- b0 + b2*time[t] + b1*one[t] + b3*two[t] + b4*three[t] + b5*i1[t] + b6*i2[t] + b7*i4[t]
  }
  b0 ~ dnorm(mu0,tau0)
  b1 ~ dnorm(mu1,tau1)
  b2 ~ dnorm(mu2,tau2)
  b3 ~ dnorm(mu3,tau3)
  b4 ~ dnorm(mu4,tau4)
  b5 ~ dnorm(mu5,tau5)
  b6 ~ dnorm(mu6,tau6)
  b7 ~ dnorm(mu7,tau7)
  
  mu0 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu1 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu2 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu3 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu4 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu5 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu6 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  mu7 ~ dnorm(0,1e4)
  
  tau0 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau1 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau2 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau3 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau4 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau5 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau6 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tau7 ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
  tauC ~ dgamma(0.01,0.01)
}

write.model(mod, "bayesPiece.txt")

dataM <- list(one = data$one,
              two = data$two,
              three = data$three,
              four = data$four,
              time = data$time,
              price = data$price,
              inter = data$inter,
              i1 = data$i1,
              i2 = data$i2,
              i3 = data$i3,
              i4 = data$i4)

inits <- list(list(
                   mu0 = 0,
                   mu1 = 0,
                   mu2 = 0,
                   mu3 = 0,
                   mu4 = 0,
                   mu5 = 0,
                   mu6 = 0,
                   mu7 = 0,
                   tau0 = 1,
                   tau1 = 1,
                   tau2 = 1,
                   tau3 = 1,
                   tau4 = 1,
                   tau5 = 1,
                   tau6 = 1,
                   tau7 = 1,
                   tauC = 1
                   ))
parameters <- c("b0","b1","b2","b3","b4","b5", "b6", "b7",
                "mu0","mu1","mu2","mu3","mu4","mu5","mu6","mu7",
"tau0","tau1","tau2","tau3","tau4","tau5","tau6","tau7","tauC","eta")
mod.sim <- bugs(dataM, inits, parameters, "bayesPiece.txt",n.chains=1,
                n.burnin=10000, n.iter=20000,
                OpenBUGS.pgm=OpenBUGS.pgm,
                WINE=WINE, WINEPATH=WINEPATH,useWINE=T)


coes <- mod.sim$summary[,1]

COMPARISON

The fitted values for the Frequentist and Bayesian Models are surprisingly similar (See Graph1 and Graph2). The coefficients aren’t perfectly matched, but overall they are close. Using a hierarchical model allowed for some flexibility in letting the data determine the hyperparameters, perhaps leading to a better fit.

Since our priors are relatively non-informative it makes sense that the output would be incredibly similar to the ML estimate. Since there’s not a HUGE amount of data, I would guess that priors would pretty strongly effect the results, but I’d have to try out a few different informative priors to be sure. It’s possible the signal in the data is strong enough to overwhelm most reasonable priors.

NOTE: The coefs in the Bayesian Model (b5-b7) should be treated as offsets from b0 whereas in the Frequentist model, the coefficients are not offsets. for example \(b0 \approx \$inter 3\), but \(b5 \neq \$inter 1\)
